With settings 1 and 2 the uninformed search system performed better than the intelligent search system. This has two reasons. On the one hand the intelligent search system decided in 4 of the 6 runs to search the room \textit{home2} first, so a lot of time was lost searching there. A more detailed description of the search behavior in these runs is given in the next section. In the other two cases, where the room \textit{home1} was searched first, the remote was found quickly. On the other hand the uninformed search system found the remote relatively quickly because the remote could be seen from a view pose, where the robot could cover many occupied cells, which makes it a preferred view pose. Only once the remote was missed at the beginning, which, together with navigation problems, resulted in the one longer search time of the uninformed search system.

The search times for setting 3 highly depended on the direction the robot started to explore. In Figure \ref{explore_split} can be seen that the exploration from starting pose 1 can go either first towards room \textit{home3} (image (a)) or towards room \textit{home2} (image (b)). Case (a) was found to happen about twice as often as case (b). In case (a) the intelligent search system first searched the room \textit{home3}, which cost some time, before the room \textit{home2} was discovered and the object was found. This problem of exploration versus exploitation is described in more detail in the next section. In case (b) the mouse was found quickly. On the other hand the uninformed search system performed better in case (a) because then the exploration ended near the searched mouse and the mouse was found quickly. This is shown in Figure \ref{mouse_uninf}.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/home_search/explore1.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/home_search/explore2.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption{Possible starts of the exploration from starting pose 1}
\label{explore_split}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth, trim=800 800 100 0, clip]{figures/home_search/stupid_fast_mouse.png}
\caption[Uninformed search of mouse]{Uninformed search of mouse: The trajectories during exploration (blue) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan) and final pose, where object was found (purple)}
\label{mouse_uninf}
\end{figure}


The intelligent search system found the object very quickly in setting 4 because the robot recognized that it was already in a promising room, so only this room was explored and the mouse was found quickly. The uninformed search system was also relatively quick in this setting as the mouse could be seen from a preferred view pose, where many cells were covered.

With test settings 5, 6, 7 and 8 the intelligent search system performed much better than the uninformed search system. The uninformed search system needed more time in these settings because the searched objects were positioned at locations where they couldn't be seen form view poses which covered a lot of cells. As the uninformed search used these poses in the beginning of the search it took some time in this mode to find the searched object. The intelligent search system always selected the correct room to search with these settings and most of the time the object was found quickly. In Figure \ref{spoons} the search trajectories for setting 7 and 8 of the intelligent search system are depicted.
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth, trim=0 0 0 0, clip]{figures/example_runs/spoon.png}
\caption[Search trajectories for the intelligent search system in settings 7 and 8]{Search trajectories for the intelligent search system in settings 7 and 8: The trajectories during the exploration (blue), the move through doorway tasks (red) and the search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan) and final pose, where object was found (purple); only the map of room \textit{home1} is shown}
\label{spoons}
\end{figure}

The search trajectory lengths show slightly different results because switching high-level tasks and executing the peek tasks has no impact. Further the search trajectory lengths are not affected by navigation problems because there the robot does not move. The navigation problems have a big impact on the necessary time to search the room \textit{home2}, which consists mainly of narrow areas, as can be seen in the results of the intelligent search in setting 1. However, the trajectory lengths ignore the rotations of the robot, so the search time is still the better measurement for the search performance.

To wrap things up, the intelligent active object search system performs much better than the uninformed system except if there exist multiple rooms with similar probability to contain the object. In this case a lot of time is lost by completely searching a room not containing the object. 

\subsection{Qualitative Evaluation of the Proposed System}

\subsubsection{Search within a room}

The trajectories of the test runs of the intelligent search system with settings 7 and 8, where a spoon was searched, are depicted in Figure \ref{spoons}. Out of the figure it can be seen that the search within a room works very well most of the time. In run (b) and (f) the object was found in one of the first generated view poses, while in run (a), (c) and (e) the search took a bit longer. These small differences are mainly due to the starting position of the robot. In run (d) the object was missed at the beginning, so most of the room was searched before the table with the searched spoon was investigated again.

Test runs for the search within a room were also executed in the room \textit{lab1}. A bowl was hidden in the kitchen part in the top left corner of the room. In image (a) of Figure \ref{lab_e} the trajectory of one of those test runs is shown. The exploration took most of the search time. After the exploration the robot drove to some view poses in its vicinity and then immediately to the kitchen area and found the object. Also some test runs were executed with disabled exploration. The trajectory of one of those runs is shown in image (b) of Figure \ref{lab_e}. In this run the kitchen area was not found for a long time and much time was lost searching in unlikely areas. This shows the benefit of executing an exploration task before the search task.
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[with exploration]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth, trim=0 0 0 100, clip]{figures/example_runs/lab_5.png}} &
\subfloat[without exploration]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth, trim=400 200 500 100, clip]{figures/example_runs/lab10.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption[Search for a bowl in the room \textit{lab1}]{Search for a bowl in the room \textit{lab1}: The bowl is hidden in the kitchen area in the top left corner. The trajectories during exploration (blue) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan) and final pose, where object was found (purple)}
\label{lab_e}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Search in environments with multiple rooms}

In the test runs shown in Figure \ref{spoons} always the room containing the object was searched first. 

As already mentioned in Section \ref{tests}, with setting 2, where a remote is hidden in room \textit{home1}, the robot sometimes chooses to search for the remote first in room \textit{home2} and sometimes first in room \textit{home1}. The former is shown in image (a) of Figure \ref{remotes}, the latter in image (b). In Table \ref{remote_tab} the object probabilities and expected search times are stated for both rooms and runs. In run (a) the room \textit{home2} was favored because the lower object probability in room \textit{home2} was offset by the much lower expected search time, which made \textit{home2} the optimal next room to search. In run (b) the difference in the object probabilities was big enough for room \textit{home1} being the optimal choice. In both runs the robot correctly recognized that room \textit{home3} was unlikely to contain the searched remote.
\begin{table}[h!]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|c|c|}
\hline
run & (a) & (b)\\ \hline
object probability in \textit{home1} & 0.213 & 0.249\\ \hline
expected search time in \textit{home1} & 616\,s & 563\,s\\ \hline
object probability in \textit{home2} & 0.158 & 0.153\\ \hline
expected search time in \textit{home2} & 360\,s & 438\,s\\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Object probabilities and expected search times in room \textit{home1} and room \textit{home2} for two runs shown in Figure \ref{remotes}}
\label{remote_tab}
\end{table}
\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[angle=90,origin=c,width=0.47\textwidth]{figures/example_runs/remote1.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[angle=90,origin=c,width=0.47\textwidth]{figures/example_runs/remote2.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption[Example runs of searches for a remote]{Example runs of searches for a remote: The trajectories during exploration (blue), move through doorway (red) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan), the final pose, where object was found (purple), and the connections of the paths over room borders (red lines); room \textit{home1} is at the bottom, room \textit{home2} is on the top right and room \textit{home3} is on the top left}
\label{remotes}
\end{figure}

The robot sometimes makes suboptimal decision when no likely room was discovered yet. In Figure \ref{remotes} two search runs with test setting 3, where a mouse is hidden in room \textit{home2}, are depicted. In the run shown in (a) the robot first entered room \textit{home3} and as both visited rooms had a low probability for containing the searched mouse, the smaller room \textit{home3} was searched. Only after that the room \textit{home2} was discovered and the mouse was found. In the run shown in (b) the room \textit{home2} was discovered first and the mouse was found quickly. In both runs the robot correctly recognized that room \textit{home1} was less likely to contain a mouse than room \textit{home2}.
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[angle=90,origin=c,width=0.47\textwidth]{figures/example_runs/mouse1.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[angle=90,origin=c,width=0.47\textwidth]{figures/example_runs/mouse2.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption[Example runs of searches for a mouse]{Example runs of searches for a remote: The trajectories during exploration (blue), move through doorway (red) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan), the final pose, where object was found (purple), and the connections of the paths over room borders (red lines); room \textit{home1} is at the bottom, room \textit{home2} is on the top right and room \textit{home3} is on the top left}
\label{explore_split}
\end{figure}

In Figure \ref{wine1} a search for a wine glass hidden in the kitchen of the institute environment is shown. In this run the kitchen was the last room which was discovered. The search in the bathroom was postponed, but in two other unlikely rooms a search was executed. This is similar to the above mentioned search run for the mouse, where the robot prefers to searches a small, unlikely room before exploring a larger, unlikely room. After discovering the kitchen the robot correctly recognized that the kitchen was the most promising room to search. 
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth, trim=200 0 0 0, clip]{figures/example_runs/wine2.png}
\caption[Search for a wine glass in the institute environment]{Search for a wine glass in the institute environment: The wine glass is in the kitchen (bottom left room). The trajectories during exploration (blue), move through doorway (red) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan), the final pose, where object was found (purple), and the connections of the paths over room borders (red lines) }
\label{wine1}
\end{figure}

In Figure \ref{toilet} a search for a toilet in the institute environment is depicted. In this run the robot correctly recognized all discovered rooms to be unlikely to contain a toilet until the bathroom was found, where the toilet was found.
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth, trim=800 700 0 0, clip]{figures/example_runs/toilet.png}
