\label{toilet}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Search in explored environments}

In Figure \ref{explored} two runs in the already explored institute environment are shown. On the left a search for a toilet, which was seen during exploration, is shown. Except for some problems with the movement on the slippery floor the robot directly drove to the bathroom and found the toilet. On the right a wine glass was search, which had been put out of a cupboard after the exploration, so the robot did not know it is there. However, the robot recognized that the kitchen was the most likely location for a wine glass and immediately drove there and found the object. 

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/example_runs/toilet_exp.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/example_runs/wine_glass_exp.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption[Search runs in the explored institute environment]{Search runs in the explored institute environment: Search for a toilet (a) and search for a wine glass(b)}
\label{explored}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Summary}

To recap the findings in the test runs, the search within a room is efficient because areas more likely to contain the object are searched first and the object is usually found quickly. In environments with multiple rooms the proposed system makes suboptimal decisions if no room, which is likely to contain the searched object, is found. This problem of weighting exploration versus exploitation is difficult to solve. However, when the discovered rooms have either a high or very low probability to contain the object, reasonable decisions are made by the robot, which lead to efficient active object searches.